<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<text id="01-criteria" title="Segmentation Criteria Types">
  <summary>Four segmentation criteria types — demographic, behavioral, psychographic, needs-based — with use-case guidance for each.</summary>

  <section title="Demographic Segmentation">
    <p>Variables: age, income, education, occupation, company size, industry. Best for B2B targeting and pricing tier design where company size or role title directly correlates with budget authority and purchasing process.</p>
    <antipattern>
      <description>Using demographic segments alone for messaging work.</description>
      <reason>Demographics consistently underperform behavior-and-needs segments for messaging because they capture who someone is, not what they need or do. Age 25-34 tells you nothing about their workflow or pain intensity.</reason>
    </antipattern>
  </section>

  <section title="Behavioral Segmentation">
    <p>Variables: usage frequency (daily/weekly/monthly), purchase history (free/paid/churned), feature usage (core only vs power user), engagement (active/passive/dormant), buying stage (aware/considering/ready). Best for product development and retention strategies.</p>
    <rule>
      <statement>Prefer behavioral dimensions from observed CRM or analytics data over self-reported survey data. Observable behavior is more reliable than stated intention.</statement>
      <rationale>Users over-report their engagement and under-report their churn risk in surveys. Behavioral data from product analytics captures actual usage regardless of stated preference.</rationale>
    </rule>
  </section>

  <section title="Psychographic Segmentation">
    <p>Variables: values (quality over price, innovation), attitudes (risk-tolerant vs skeptical), lifestyle (work-life balance vs hustle), motivations (status, security, creativity), pain tolerance ("just make it work" vs perfectionist). Best for messaging and brand positioning.</p>
    <rule>
      <statement>Only include a psychographic dimension if it maps to a measurable data source you actually have. Dimensions like "growth mindset" cannot be measured and produce hallucinated segments.</statement>
      <rationale>LLMs generate plausible psychographic segments from training data priors. Without an observable data source, the segment is fiction.</rationale>
    </rule>
  </section>

  <section title="Needs-Based Segmentation">
    <p>Variables: problem severity (critical/moderate/nice-to-have), current solution (DIY/competitor/nothing), budget (limited/flexible/unlimited), speed priority (urgent vs can wait), support needs (self-serve/guided/white-glove). Best for product tier design and pricing strategy.</p>
    <p>Needs-based segments often align most directly with pricing tier boundaries and feature gating decisions, making them the most actionable type for a solopreneur product with limited engineering capacity.</p>
  </section>
</text>
